
    dovs is a small companion utility to the docker-ovs image. It helps with:

    - running multiple independant OVS instances (nodes)
    - attaching network namespaces to such instances (guests)
    - Setup overlay networks with the help of a running ODL instance.

    In regards to ODL, genius and a neutron provider must be installed.

    Examples:

     Run a OVS instance and attach a guest namespace:
      > dovs.py add-node --name node-1
      > dovs.py add-guest --name guest-1 --ip 10.0.0.1/24

     Something more elaborated, with ODL providing overlay networking:
      > dovs.py add-node --name node-1 --odl 192.168.56.1
      > dovs.py add-node --name node-2 --odl 192.168.56.1
      > dovs.py add-net --name subnet-A --prefix 10.0.0.1/24 --odl 192.168.56.1
      > dovs.py add-net --name subnet-B --prefix 10.0.0.1/24 --odl 192.168.56.1
      > dovs.py add-guest --name guest-1 --ip 10.0.0.1/24 --net subnet-A --odl 192.168.56.1 --node node-1
      > dovs.py add-guest --name guest-2 --ip 10.0.0.1/24 --net subnet-B --odl 192.168.56.1 --node node-1
      > dovs.py add-guest --name guest-3 --ip 10.0.0.2/24 --net subnet-A --odl 192.168.56.1 --node node-2
      > dovs.py add-guest --name guest-4 --ip 10.0.0.2/24 --net subnet-B --odl 192.168.56.1 --node node-2

     Similar thing can be achieved with one spawn command
      > sudo ./dovs.py spawn --nodes 2 --guests 2 --nets 2 --odl 192.168.56.1

     Afterwards SFC-ODL configuration (SF and Logical SFF) could be set
     base on networking previously created
      > sudo ./dovs.py sfc-config --cfg-from-net --odl 192.168.56.1

     Command that creates networking and SFC-ODL configuration base on
     the list of chains (--chains "['firewall, napt44', 'napt44']") and
     creates other nodes base on their names (--node-names client1,client2,server)
     (see RESULT.txt file for execution output)
      echo sudo ./dovs.py clean --odl 192.168.99.100 > RESULT.txt
      sudo ./dovs.py clean --odl 192.168.99.100 >> RESULT.txt
      echo sudo ./dovs.py sfc-config --node-names client1,client2,server --chains \"[\'firewall, napt44\', \'napt44\']\" --odl 192.168.99.100 >> RESULT.txt ; echo >> RESULT.txt
      sudo ./dovs.py sfc-config --node-names client1,client2,server --chains "['firewall, napt44', 'napt44']" --odl 192.168.99.100 >> RESULT.txt
